biscotti.collect

Class TreeQueue<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
        • biscotti.collect.TreeQueue<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of elements held in this queue
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    SortedCollection<E>, Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Queue<E>

    public final class TreeQueue<E>
extends AbstractQueue<E>
implements SortedCollection<E>, Cloneable, Serializable
    An unbounded priority Queue based on a modified Red-Black Tree. The elements of this queue are sorted according to their natural ordering, or by an explicit Comparator provided at creation. Attempting to remove or insert null elements is prohibited. Querying for null elements is allowed. Inserting non-comparable elements will result in a ClassCastException. This queue uses the same general ordering rules as a PriorityQueue. The first element (the head) of this queue is considered to be the least element with respect to the specified ordering. A comparator is used (whether or not one is explicitly provided) to perform all element comparisons. Two elements which are deemed equal by the comparator's compare(E, E) method have equal priority from the standpoint of this queue. Elements with equal priority are sorted according to their insertion order.

    Besides the regular peek(), poll(), remove() operations specified in the Queue interface, this implementation provides additional peekLast(), pollLast(), removeLast() methods to examine the elements at the tail of the queue.

    The iterator() and descendingIterator() methods return fail-fast iterators which are guaranteed to traverse the elements of the queue in ascending and descending priority order, respectively. Attempts to modify the elements in this queue at any time after an iterator is created, in any way except through the iterator's own remove method, will result in a ConcurrentModificationException.

    This queue is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this queue concurrently it must be synchronized externally.

    The underlying Red-Black Tree provides the following running time compared to a PriorityQueue (where n is the size of this queue and m is the size of the specified collection which is iterable in linear time):

    Method Running Time
    TreeQueue
    (worst-case)    		 PriorityQueue
    (worst-case)
    addAll(Collection)
    containsAll(Collection)
    retainAll(Collection)
    removeAll(Collection)     		O(m log n)
    add(E)
    offer(E)
    remove(Object)     		O(log n)
    contains(Object) O(log n) O(n)

    poll()

        public static <E> TreeQueue<E> create(Collection<? extends E> elements)
        Creates a new TreeQueue containing the specified initial elements. If elements is an instance of SortedSet , PriorityQueue, MinMaxPriorityQueue, or SortedCollection this queue will be ordered according to the same ordering. Otherwise, this queue will be ordered according to the natural ordering of its elements.
